user: behavior in more detail. Genetic studies also contribute, by revealing how populations remain connected over large geographical distances and how migratory and non-migratory populations differ. The challenges butterflies face during migration are significant. They must find enough nectar along the route, avoid predators and bad weather, and reach their destination before conditions become too harsh. Human actions can make this harder. Habitat loss and fragmentation, herbicide use that kills host plants like milkweed, deforestation in overwintering sites, urbanization, and climate change all influence migratory butterflies. For monarchs in North America, the loss of overwintering forest in Mexico and the decline of the most important signals. As days grow shorter in late summer and early autumn, the combination of decreasing day length and changing temperature can cause developing monarch larvae and pupae to become the “migratory generation.” Hormonal changes associated with this developmental path lead to the long-lived, non-reproductive adults that are primed for migration rather than immediate breeding. In many species, a similar interaction between photoperiod and temperature triggers migratory behavior. Wind patterns are another big factor. Butterflies are not strong enough to power through unfavorable winds over long distances, so selection has favored behavior that takes advantage of tailwinds and avoids strong headwinds. On days with favorable winds, large numbers of butterflies may take off together, resulting in impressive mass movements that observers can see even on weather radar. When winds are unfavorable, butterflies often rest, feed, and wait. This interplay between behavior and weather means that migration timing can vary from year to year. Another aspect worth noting is that butterfly migration is not always a neatly organized, single-wave movement. In many species, it’s more like a broad, population-level tendency. Some individuals may travel